    <h4>Field performance of rootstocks</h4>
    A wide variety of citrus rootstock cultivars are available for use in citrus propagation, including the 16 released by USDA.  The most reliable information about how a rootstock will perform in graft combination with a fruiting scion cultivar is obtained by data collection and careful comparisons among numerous rootstocks over multiple years in replicated field trials.
    <br>
    <br>
    <center><img src="/img/citrusgreening/rootstocks/Valencia.png" height="450"></center>
    <br>
    <br>
    In the following section, partial results are presented from replicated field trials which are incomplete or in progress, and will be updated as new information becomes available.  While firm conclusions from the trials, and major decisions based on trials, should await multiyear trial summaries and refereed publication of trial results, these interim summaries of results can be helpful as an aid in planning, and to use in comparison with results from other trials.  New hybrid rootstocks which demonstrate outstanding performance in field trials are typically released by USDA for public use shortly after the completion of supporting trials.  Additional information on rootstock characteristics and field performance can be found in the publications listed at the end of this section.
